  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA291-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu parattaiyiṉ piriya (EV: /) vāyilāyp pukka pāṇaṉukkut (C1: vāyilākap pukka pāṇaṟkut) tōḻi talaimakaḷatu kuṟippaṟintu neruṅkic colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said, for [HIM] after understanding HIS intention, to the bard who had entered as a mediator when [HE] had separated for another woman.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA291">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nīrpeyarntu māṟiya ceṟicēṟ ṟaḷḷa</l>
<l>            ṉeyttalaik koḻumī ṉarunta viṉakkuruku</l>
<l>            kuppai veṇmaṇa lēṟi yaraica</l>
<l>            roṇpaṭait tokutiyi ṉilaṅkit tōṉṟun</l>
<l>            taṇperum pauvanīrt tuṟaivaṟku nīyuṅ </l>
<l rend="indent4">            teṇṭiraip pauvat taṇṭuṟaic cērppaṟkuk</l>
<l>            kaṇṭāṅ kuraiyāy kuṇamō pāṇa</l>
<l>            māyiru muḷḷūr maṉṉaṉ māvūrn</l>
<l>            tellit tarīiya viṉaniraip</l>
<l>            pallāṉ kiḻavari ṉaḻintaviva ṇalaṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Talk as you have seen for yourself, bard,</l>
<l rend="indent">to the man from the ghat by the water of the cool big ocean,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the herons in groups, mounted on the heaped white sand,</l>
<l rend="indent3">when they eat the rich fish with oily heads</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the dense muddy mire that has been changed</l>
<l rend="indent3">as the water has moved,</l>
<l rend="indent">appear shining as a collection of the king’s bright weapons,<note place="foot">Or, as T.V.G. understands it, "as a multitude of brightly armoured king’s [warriors]".</note></l>
<l>– of the quality<note place="foot">The problem with this solution is that it does not take into account the particle -<term xml:lang="ta">ō</term> marking <term xml:lang="ta">kuṇam</term>. We might, however, consider the possibility that this is the -<term xml:lang="ta">ō</term> often accompanying (and slightly softening?) the imperative, which is affixed instead to the post-positioned direct object.</note> of her beauty that perished, as the owner of many cows</l>
<l rend="indent3">in a long(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iṉam nirai</term>: what kind of information is added to <term xml:lang="ta">nirai</term> by this epithet? Does <term xml:lang="ta">iṉam</term> here just refer to the cows being numerous?</note> row, when the king mounts [his] horse</l>
<l rend="indent4">in the big dark inner village [and] takes<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tarīiya</term>: strange here the choice of <term xml:lang="ta">taru</term>, which should be either give or bring in a direction towards. However, the point of the comparison can only be the disappearance of cattle.</note> [them] at night.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="6+9b">
<l>You don’t talk as if you had seen it yourself, of her beauty.</l>
<l>[Is that] virtue, bard?</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
